  "description": "When a new user signs up, we want them to have their own OpenRouter key. Create a new OpenRouter key and store their key hashed. When the user logs in, we want to use this key in all API requests.\n\nYes — OpenRouter is actually well-suited for exactly this multi-tenant use case. Here's the full picture:\n\n---\n\n## Per-Tenant API Keys on OpenRouter\n\n**Yes, you can absolutely do this.** OpenRouter provides endpoints to programmatically manage your API keys, enabling key creation and management for applications that need to distribute or rotate keys automatically. A key use case is SaaS Applications — automatically creating unique API keys for each customer instance.\n\n---\n\n## How It Works\n\n### 1. Create a Provisioning API Key (one-time setup)\n\nGo to the Provisioning API Keys page in your OpenRouter settings, click \"Create New Key,\" and complete the process. Provisioning keys cannot be used to make API calls to OpenRouter's completion endpoints — they are exclusively for key management operations.\n\nStore this in your Next.js app as a server-side env variable (`OPENROUTER_PROVISIONING_KEY`).\n\n### 2. Programmatically Create Keys Per Tenant\n\nYou call `/api/v1/keys` from your backend to mint a key for each tenant at onboarding time:\n\n```ts\n// app/api/tenants/[id]/provision-key/route.ts (Next.js Route Handler)\nimport { NextResponse } from 'next/server';\n\nexport async function POST(req: Request, { params }: { params: { id: string } }) {\n  const tenantId = params.id;\n\n  const response = await fetch('https://openrouter.ai/api/v1/keys', {\n    method: 'POST',\n    headers: {\n      'Authorization': `Bearer ${process.env.OPENROUTER_PROVISIONING_KEY}`,\n      'Content-Type': 'application/json',\n    },\n    body: JSON.stringify({\n      name: `Tenant: ${tenantId}`,\n      limit: 500,           // optional credit limit\n      limit_reset: 'monthly', // resets every month\n    }),\n  });\n\n  const { key, hash } = await response.json();\n\n  // Store key hash in your DB for future management\n  // Store key itself securely for the tenant to use\n  await db.tenant.update({ where: { id: tenantId }, data: { orKeyHash: hash } });\n\n  return NextResponse.json({ success: true });\n}\n```\n\n> ⚠️ **Important:** The actual key string is only returned at creation time. Store the `hash` in your DB for future updates/deletions, and store the key itself in a secrets manager (or Salesforce / your DB encrypted field).\n\n---\n\n## What You Get Per Key\n\nAPI responses include usage tracking at daily, weekly, and monthly granularity — `usage`, `usage_daily`, `usage_weekly`, `usage_monthly` — plus `limit_remaining` and the ability to disable keys or reset limits on a schedule.\n\nThis means you can:\n- **See per-tenant usage** via the OpenRouter dashboard or by polling `/api/v1/keys/{hash}`\n- **Set credit caps** so one tenant can't blow the budget\n- **Disable a key** when a tenant churns\n\n---\n\n## Architecture Recommendation for Hub+\n\nSince you're building a multi-tenant SaaS on Next.js, I'd suggest this pattern:\n\n| Layer | What to do |\n|---|---|\n| **Provisioning** | Create key via API during tenant onboarding flow |\n| **Storage** | Store key hash in your DB; store actual key in an env-level secrets vault |\n| **Usage tracking** | Poll `/api/v1/keys/{hash}` or use OpenRouter's activity export (CSV/PDF) |\n| **Limits** | Set per-tenant `limit` + `limit_reset: 'monthly'` to align with billing cycles |\n| **Offboarding** | Call `DELETE /api/v1/keys/{hash}` when tenant churns |\n\nThis maps well to the tranche-based billing model you're building — you could even tie the `limit` value directly to the tier/tranche a tenant is on and update it when they upgrade.\n\nWant me to build out a full Next.js API route module for tenant key provisioning, usage polling, and disable/delete operations?",
